star  aBringing together the views of expatriate, exiled, and émigré feminists from various parts of the world, this collection explores themes of exile, home, displacement, and the practice of feminism across national boundaries.The thirteen articles presented here originated with a conference on émigré feminism held at Trent University in October 1996. The authors, most of them now living in Canada, are scholars from South Africa, Chile, Trinidad and Tobago, Greece, Hungary, the Czech Republic, Turkey, Iran, Finland and New Zealand. Their views have been shaped by their experience of specific political and economic changes, such as the dismantling of communism or apartheid, the rise of religious fundamentalism, or rapid marketization. Together the essays offer a rich diversity of intellectual, political, cultural, and religious perspectives.This book adds a new dimension to our understanding of expatriation by putting a feminist face on the émigré experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFeminismvCross-cultural studiesvCongresses. 0aFeminismzCanadavCongresses. 0aWomen immigrantszCanadavCongresses. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh1 aArat-Koc, Sedef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBobb Smith, Yvonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeitlinger, Alena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeitlinger, Alena, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJung, Nóra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKamboureli, Smaro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarpinski, Eva C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManicom, Linzi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula